{"cursor":"18918","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn philosophy, 'term logic', also known as 'traditional logic' or\n'[[Aristotelianism|Aristotelian]] logic', is a loose name for the way of doing\nlogic that began with Aristotle and that was dominant until the advent of modern\npredicate logic in the late nineteenth century. This entry is an introduction to\nthe term logic needed to understand philosophy texts written before predicate\nlogic came to be seen as the only formal logic of interest. Readers lacking a\ngrasp of the basic terminology and ideas of term logic can have difficulty\nunderstanding such texts, because their authors typically assumed an\nacquaintance with term logic.\n","linknr":578,"url":"Term_logic","recorded":1362554646,"links":26,"instances":["logic","philosopher","mathematics","traditional_logic","logic"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Logic","Term logic|","Philosophical logic","History of logic","Aristotle","Classical logic"],"headings":["Aristotle's system","The basics","The term","The proposition","Singular terms","Influence on philosophy","Decline of term logic","A revival","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Aristoteles_Louvre.jpg/100px-Aristoteles_Louvre.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Socrates_blue_version2.png/20px-Socrates_blue_version2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Logical_connectives_Hasse_diagram.svg/20px-Logical_connectives_Hasse_diagram.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["function","mathematics"],["gareth_evans","philosopher"],["contraposition","traditional_logic"],["conversion","logic"],["transposition","logic"],["gareth_evans","philosopher"]],"members":["transposition","gareth_evans"